article.headline: Randolph scores career-high 34 after apology
article.linkText: Blazers get it done without Bonzi
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Zach Randolph said he was sorry, went back to work and had the highest point total of his NBA career. Randolph scored 34 points and grabbed nine rebounds after publicly apologizing for his recent arrest, leading the Trail Portland Blazers to a 97-95 overtime victory over the Indiana Pacers on Wednesday night. "I was thinking about the game all day today, trying to keep my focus on basketball," said Randolph, who was arrested early Tuesday after a police officer said he smelled marijuana in the forward's car during a traffic stop. The victory was a dramatic ending to an eventful day that also included the trade of Bonzi Wells to Memphis. Reggie Miller made a 3-pointer with 28.5 seconds left to put the Pacers up 95-94 before Damon Stoudamire answered with 14-foot jumper. After a timeout, Indiana's Ron Artest slipped while driving under the basket and lost control of the ball. Anthony Johnson then fouled Stoudamire, who made the first of a pair of free throws with 0.8 seconds left for the final margin. Johnson tried to lob the ball to Jermaine O'Neal as the clock ran out, but Portland's Ruben Patterson knocked it down. "We stuck it out together," Randolph said. "It was a great win, a great comeback. Everybody played well, played together as a team. Damon hit big shots. Jeff played well, Dale, Rasheed, everybody." After Randolph's arrest on Tuesday, the Blazers made more news by trading troubled guard Wells to Memphis for Wesley Person and a conditional first-round draft pick. Stoudamire had 17 points and five assists for the Blazers, who improved their home record to 9-2. Artest, who missed Indiana's win Monday at Phoenix because of back spasms, had 21 points and six rebounds. "I don't know what happened," Artest said about the fall. "I just went on the floor. There were a lot of little things that happened where we would have won this game tonight." A few hours after the Wells trade was announced, Randolph made his first public comments since being accused of driving under the influence. "I am up here to apologize to my teammates, to the organization and to the Portland fans," Randolph said. "This is an embarrassment, and it is a distraction to the team. I can't talk about what happened, but I want to apologize to all you guys." Randolph, who leads the team in both points and rebounds, was greeted with a mixture of cheers and boos when his name was announced before the game. "He was big for us, making shots to keep it close," coach Maurice Cheeks said. "He tried to forget about everything that has gone on the last couple of days." The Blazers pulled to 80-79 in regulation on Stoudamire's two free throws with 2:11 left, but Johnson's 3-pointer with 26.1 seconds left gave Indiana what appeared to be a comfortable 86-81 lead. Stoudamire hit a 3-pointer with 12 seconds left to narrow it to 87-86. And after Indiana's made just one of a pair of free throws, Stoudamire's layup with 2.2 seconds to go tied it. Miller's off-balance jumper missed, sending the game into overtime. The Pacers opened their road trip with a loss to the Lakers, but rebounded with a 89-82 victory over the Suns. O'Neal, traded from the Blazers to Indiana before the 2000-01 season, had 18 points and 11 rebounds.

Game notes
After the Wells trade, the Trail Blazers activated forward Travis Outlaw, the team's top draft pick, who had been on injured list with tendinitis in his knees since Nov. 19. ... Former Indiana Pacers coach Bobby "Slick" Leonard was hospitalized in Portland on Wednesday after having chest pains Tuesday night. Leonard, currently a broadcaster for the team, was under observation and was expected to be released Friday. ... Wallace wore Wells' personalized sweat band on his upper arm.
